When core service agencies are initiated, the Secretary shall:
Define the priority populations to be served by the core service agencies, with a special emphasis on the provision of services to the seriously mentally ill populations;
Define the essential mental health and associated support services to be provided under the auspices of the core service agencies;
Define the essential administrative functions to be carried out by core service agencies; and
Outline the requirements for the core service agencies' governance structure.

To assure the continuing provision of appropriate services, the Secretary shall:
Annually review and may approve the core service agencies' program plan;
In conjunction with the appropriate authorities, establish and maintain a funding mechanism for the core service agencies which may include the allocation of funds for inpatient services;
Develop a mechanism whereby any unexpended funds remaining at the end of the year shall remain with the core service agencies or the community providers;
Establish procedures to facilitate intraagency and interagency linkages at State and local levels with the core service agencies; and
Establish procedures within the Mental Hygiene Administration for a process regarding program, policy, or contract disputes that gives all community mental health programs regulated by the Administration the right to:
Access the mediation process established by the Administration; and
If dissatisfied with the outcome of the mediation by the Administration, request a hearing with the Office of Administrative Hearings in accordance with Title 10, Subtitle 2 of the State Government Article.
